It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

My journey into the social work field has been a pursuit of a path to help children who have faced abuse or neglect, and to support troubled families. The values I bring to this field include service, respect, ethical integrity, and a commitment to enhance relationships within families and myself, ensuring I stay competent in my field. These values resonate deeply with my personal beliefs.

I've always harbored a desire to assist others, but the specific career path eluded me through high school and college. Many individuals evaded their problems through denial, while others resorted to less-than-healthy coping mechanisms. Witnessing these situations solidified my decision to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Post-graduation, I took a break from the academic world. One summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a troubled teenager. He was escaping his abusive parents, and the next day, he involved the police. I drove to his parents' house to offer help, and though the law couldn't intervene, I spoke with his parents. They were defensive and blamed his “manipulative” behavior for involving outsiders. This encounter sparked my interest in social work, seeing it as a way to help children navigate family disputes.

Social justice is another core value in this field. Our society claims to value individuality but often follows archaic traditions, making it challenging to be truly unique. I've protested against this contradiction throughout my education. I dyed my hair, wore non-conforming clothes, pierced my ears, joined GSBA, and stood up against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice and will continue to advocate for it.

The following paper delves into the Biological and Sociocultural models as they pertain to insomnia. The Biological model centers on genetic inheritance and medical health aspects, while the Sociocultural model examines environmental factors, including race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review explores these models through a selection of research studies, explaining each and critiquing their strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be categorized as either primary or secondary. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias and Parasomnias, while sleep disorders related to other mental disorders are linked to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Dyssomnias, such as Primary Insomnia and Hypersomnia, deal with initiating or maintaining sleep, while Parasomnias like Nightmare Disorder and Sleepwalking Disorder affect sleep behavior. The following review zeroes in on insomnia and its relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The Biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiological aspects. Orexin-producing neurons in the hypothalamus play a crucial role in regulating sleep and wakefulness. Research on mice showed that specific GABAB receptors on these neurons control sleep and wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor promotes sleep, and its inhibition can reduce anxiety. A study found that the GABAB agonist (baclofen) significantly increased sleep time in mice (Matsuki et al., 2009). This indicates that animal models can be applied to human studies, suggesting a genetic and environmental basis for human sleep regulation. A dysfunction in this receptor could disrupt sleep without medication. Socioculturally, if this phenotype is inherited, altered receptors would naturally disrupt sleep, negatively impacting daily life, including school, work, and monotonous tasks that require focus.

This article explores Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD). It begins by defining the disorder, then outlines how it’s diagnosed, including common signs or “red flags,” and finally suggests ways educators can support students with CAPD in a mainstream classroom setting.

CAPD, or APD, is essentially how well our central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. The brain struggles to interpret sounds, even though hearing is normal. Those affected can't distinguish words, separate conversation from background noise, or recognize sound patterns. They might miss sarcasm or have difficulties with sound sequences.

CAPD was first recognized in the mid-1950s, initially called “auditory imperception.” Italian researchers led by Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started developing tests for affected children in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and a model for explaining how the brain processes these sounds. A national conference in 1977 further spurred research into CAPD.

Manifestations of CAPD include: not being able to locate sounds, having trouble distinguishing between sounds, missing sound patterns, misunderstanding speech changes, and difficulties with sound sequences. Diagnosis involves screening using various tools, as there’s no single diagnostic test. This might include questionnaires, observations, and tests that present multiple simultaneous sounds.

Many educators may wonder how to assist students with CAPD in a mainstream classroom. The article offers suggestions for creating an inclusive learning environment, such as simplifying instructions, reducing background noise, and providing visual aids to support auditory information.

Every day that I return to my Taipei home, I am greeted by the sight of Soggy Shubert, the piano. It brings back memories of piano and ballet lessons where I received the same criticism... if only you could learn to count! I CAN count and I could then, too! However, I remember how fun it was to just play without thinking/counting, dance without memorizing steps... it felt like flying! When I see Shubert, I remember how I could lose myself and my stress in the music and think I should start playing again... but every time I sit down with Shubert, he laughs at me. His former owner, my landlady, left him several humid summers with no air conditioner, no dehumidifier and his sound-board got wet. Now, even after tuning, it is only a matter of weeks before the pegs loosen and... well you can imagine. It is less like flying and more like crawling through... Anyway, instead of playing the piano, I go dancing at salsa clubs. Well, unfortunately, the Taiwanese way is to take lessons, memorize steps and count in my ear. I'd rather feel the music have 'sweet nothings' whispered in my ear (even if I dance badly), but whatever... at least I can leave the counting /memorizing to someone else.

German colonial rule has been widely criticized for its harshness, most notably in the case of the Ovaherero and Nama genocide in German South West Africa. However, it's important to remember that an empire as vast as the German colonial empire couldn't be understood through such a simple lens. It was characterized by a wide range of policies and ruling styles, reflected in its educational systems. For instance, when the British took over German East Africa (now Tanzania), they found a sizeable educated and literate African population. Similar praise was given to German educational efforts in colonies like Kamerun. In stark contrast, South West Africa (now Namibia) saw a completely different reality. The German government left the task of educating the natives almost entirely to mission societies with limited support, while they invested heavily in European education, establishing state schools and regulating mission schools. This had lasting effects, leaving the majority of the population uneducated and illiterate. Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this disparity. This paper aims to delve deeper into these factors, focusing on new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans. There's a considerable body of literature on German colonial education, much of it in German and written post-1900. Early works focused on describing the educational systems in these colonies, while later English works expanded the discourse through comparative studies and detailed analyses. Cohen's study, for example, compares the educational systems of South West Africa and East Africa, attributing many of the differences to the large settler population in South West Africa. Unlike Germany's other colonies, South West Africa had a moderate climate, but a significant portion of the territory was desert. This influenced the European population, with nearly 15,000 whites living there by 1913, compared to around 5,336 in East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population.

The evolution of Popular Music over the past 100 years has led to a massive array of genres, making it challenging to list them all. The sub-genres and sub-sub-genres within these genres, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have multiplied, with Heavy Metal rock becoming notably diverse and expressive in the past 40 years. This genre's flexibility has inspired numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres, creating a labyrinth of niches that define it today. The boundaries between what is considered Heavy Metal are blurred, incorporating themes from other genres. To grasp the current metal music landscape, one must first understand the movement's origins and why it's more than just a genre.

Heavy Metal is often characterized by its "more" philosophy—more bass, volume, violence, theatricality, and technical prowess. Musicians in metal bands are skilled and proficient, which resonates in their music's complexity. It has also been a movement heavily influenced by psychedelic drug culture, with the mid-70s boom leading to experimental, otherworldly records. The dark, visceral qualities of metal were innovative at the time, as most popular music lacked this emotional depth. Later generations of metal artists have drawn inspiration from the Romantic Era's dark themes. Lyrics like those from the Beatles' Helter Skelter exemplify this darkness, showcasing the genre's heavier, darker side. This song is often considered one of the first Heavy Metal tracks, a response to a Rolling Stones song, as the Beatles sought to prove they could match the Stones' intensity.

Years before the Surrealists began painting their dreamlike masterpieces, Henri Rousseau was meticulously weaving his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist, captures not just a woman marveling at the wonders of her dream land, but also Rousseau's personal dreams and aspirations as an artist. From the start, he harbored a longing for recognition, acceptance, and praise from fellow artists and art enthusiasts. However, he found himself grappling with a challenging internal conflict: should he conform to or mimic certain styles to be accepted by the critical art world he admired, or should he forge his own independent path?

To truly understand The Dream through this lens, one must first delve into Rousseau's biography. Born on May 21, 1844, in the northwest French town of Laval, Rousseau's father was a successful tinsmith and hardware dealer. Growing up, he received no formal art education and worked for France as a gabelou, or municipal toll service employee, earning the nickname douanier, or customs inspector. The passing of his first wife, Clémence, and eight infant children left him with only one daughter, Julia, and profound grief. Hence, he turned to painting for solace and new beginnings, unlike his contemporaries who often romanticized and sentimentalized peasants in their art. Rousseau was essentially a folk painter and mirrored the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.

Rousseau's obsession with gaining acceptance in the art world is somewhat understandable given his context: he was uneducated in fine arts and began his career late in life, producing art alongside well-known, talented contemporaries. Remarkably, he didn't receive proper recognition until around the same time Matisse was rising to fame. In Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon notes that while Matisse and Rousseau were competitors, they differed in style, subject matter, and their motivations for painting: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting tritely, while Rousseau desired to paint so conventionally that he would be accepted by the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have posited a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there's a profound reason for this. As John Keats wrote in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn much in life through education or experience, yet we often appreciate ethics and aesthetics seemingly without instruction. Both fields strive to explain why something is beautiful or moral, rather than prescribing rules. For instance, discussing the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might explore elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but these don't fully capture why it's good art. Instead, when asked about a favorite piece, we often say, "There's just something about it," before diving into more complex explanations. Both art and morality can't be fully reduced to descriptions of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor put it, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." Likewise, ethics has this same quality, as Wittgenstein noted, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." I believe this intangible essence, this "je ne sais quoi," is art and morality's most powerful attribute, linking them deeply. We experience both morality and art most powerfully at a noumenal level, as Kant might put it—impacting us in ways that can be felt but not fully explained. This is especially true in literature, as McKean said, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality." We value literature precisely because it reflects the values we hold in life.

Germany today stands as a powerful, unified country, blending its unique culture from the alpine peaks of Munich to the Baltic shores of Kiel. This cultural mosaic stretches from Cologne, along the Rhine, through the heart of Germany, and up to the Elbe's banks in the Saxon city of Dresden. It's no surprise, then, that modern Germany is a fusion of various sources and tribes.

Germania, the ancestral home of the Germans, has a name whose origins are debated by scholars. Some argue it came from the Germanic tribe called Tungrians, or from the Old Irish word 'garim' meaning 'to shout,' indicating the Germans' loud nature. Tacitus, a Roman historian, wrote in AD 98 that the Germans were aboriginals who did not mix with other races. He also noted that those who would leave Asia or Africa for Italy or Germany would do so only if it were their home. Similarly, Romans ventured into Germania for goods and services, but seldom stayed, leaving it to the Germanic tribes who lived on the empire's borders.

Now

I stood gazing at the scene before me, my mind void of any thoughts, passively observing the view without engaging it. I had been trained to study my surroundings with an unemotional detachment, to analyze them without connecting them to any abstract concepts. My thoughts came and went as swiftly as the objects in my field of vision. It felt as though I was not thinking at all, just experiencing what lay before me in a smooth, fluid state.

Years ago, an artist I worked with recommended to me a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had always wanted to learn to draw and this book promised to teach everything from understanding a pencil to the brain's interpretation of lines. One of its techniques was to frame any picture you want to study with a square, turning an overly detailed scene into a simplified one.

As I stared at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't impose an artist's frame on it. I was too overwhelmed by the beauty and complexity of the scene. I felt like I was looking at the beginnings of a grand piece of art, a masterpiece in the making. The first brushstroke, the first stroke of a master's brush, so to speak.

My fingers touched the brush, my hand moving through space, translating my will into action. The water in the bowl was clear and still, reflecting the light, the flakes of matter breaking away and disappearing. My hand, now more anxious and restless, hit the brush against the toilet again, but the stubborn brown package refused to budge, stuck to the bottom like a slug.

I held the mop loosely in my hand, my feet shoulder-width apart, my tie knotted tightly around my neck. I frowned as I looked at the offending package, a message left by a careless cleaner. A few more flushes, a few more moments of quiet reflection, and then I grabbed the toilet paper, wrapping it around my hand until it formed an oven mitt. I stood up straight, then bent over, my hand slowly dipping into the bowl, like a mother reaching for the Thanksgiving turkey in the oven...

Every day, our roads are claiming young lives due to a perfect storm of inexperience and adolescent inclination to take risks. The National Institutes of Health tell us that the teen brain isn't fully equipped to handle the dangers of driving, and simple inexperience leads to more fatal crashes, vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off-road incidents. Peer pressure exacerbates this, with teens often driving with friends, as anyone who's ever been young knows. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found that the more passengers a teen has, the higher the risk of accidents.

States have tried to curb teen driving fatalities by introducing temporary provisional licenses limiting driving hours and preventing other minors as passengers. However, these are mere band-aids. The real issue is that, as a group, teens are statistically ill-equipped to handle driving's risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes 18 is too young for a regular license. USA Today reports his research shows teens under 19-20 crave thrills, making it logical to delay driving until this urge diminishes. If we continue to license young teens, deaths will likely surge, especially with millions of Baby Boomer's children becoming eligible to drive by 2010.

Simplifying the law would involve maintaining driver's education classes for future drivers, but no one under 18 could drive without a full license. A provisional permit could still be issued, requiring a set number of practical training hours, likely based on current state requirements. A national, uniform law would protect teens across the nation.

This proposal is not unprecedented.

As I delved into the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all fifteen trick films made between 1895 and 1901. These films often used creative editing to create illusions. My study mainly focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and analyzing the unique traits of a few later ones. Trick films around the turn of the century were generally confined to a single set within a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, using long and medium shots, and adhering to the rule that one shot equals one film. However, some early 20th-century films dared to break these rules by incorporating multiple shots.

One striking aspect that trick films share is their filming in a set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary to capture figures or objects, drawing from the theatre and vaudeville traditions. This often constrains characters to move side-to-side within the frame, rather than towards or away from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth horizontally, without the camera following them.

Shots in trick films tend to be long and medium, with close-ups never used. This comes from the theatre tradition where the audience sees the entire performance at once. Actors rarely move towards the camera, so close-ups are absent. Most early trick films follow the pattern of one conceptual shot equaling one film, limiting their length to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second. This also restricts the dramatic usage of trick films, focusing on short, vaudeville-style tricks like magic and disappearing acts. However, a single shot may actually be several joined together to create illusions like apparition or disappearance. Carefully examine The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) to see how the "physical shot" of Mary’s severed "head" begins, despite the film's conceptual unity as a single shot.

John Taylor, from Caroline, was an early and passionate believer in Republicanism. His primary occupation as an agriculturalist, along with his brief political career, shaped him into a strong advocate for personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system underpinned his views on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and the judicial system.

Taylor saw the United States as a unique opportunity to establish an ideal system, free from established traditions that could hinder the creation of a self-governing society. He held firm beliefs in natural rights, considering them interdependent and beyond the reach of government. He argued that physical prowess and malevolent intelligence should not dictate society's rules, unlike in a state of nature.

To cultivate this ideal society, Taylor envisioned a government acknowledging both the good and evil inherent in man. He believed in a dualistic morality, stating, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protected private property, enhanced agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. He believed a government founded on such principles would function equitably, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by self-interest.

Taylor, like many other Republicans of his time, advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He sought a government with no additional rights or powers beyond what was explicitly stated, fearing an extensive Federal government could become despotic. However, he also cautioned against a strict, literal interpretation, as it could become corrupt without considering the intent of the writers. He saw the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, more explicitly describing it as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking back at Figure 17, there was a sharp decrease in commuter log submissions during the third month of our project. The reason behind this dip is unclear, although it coincides with the onset of winter in New England, which typically leads to fewer bicycle and foot commuters. The end of the fall semester, with its rush of final exams and grade processing, could also have contributed to the decline. The holiday season brings a month-long break in December, during which many do not need to come to campus. January's delayed resumption of classes may also be a factor. The low submission numbers in February, however, remain unexplained. It's possible that the initial enthusiasm for the project could have waned naturally. To reinvigorate participation, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign that resulted in a spike in log submissions. This project faced challenges in maintaining momentum due to holiday breaks and semester schedules, as well as the deeply ingrained preference for driving that characterizes our culture. We offered various prizes to encourage alternative commuting modes. These included gift certificates for local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, a bookstore, and even national chain stores. To potentially boost participation further, larger prizes like bicycles or hybrid/electric cars could have been considered. If the value of the prizes were to increase over time, this might have also helped. Initially, our gift cards seemed sufficient, but announcing a bicycle giveaway in December and a hybrid/electric car in January could have potentially increased participation and engagement rather than decrease it.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a type of security designed to track an index, commodity, or basket of assets, similar to an index fund, but with greater flexibility and stock-like trading on an exchange. It offers the diversification of an index fund along with the advantages of single stock ownership, such as short selling, buying on margin, and purchasing as few as one share per transaction. While these benefits are highly attractive, ETFs typically have lower expense ratios than mutual funds. However, there are some drawbacks too, like the need to pay a commission on trades, just as you would with stock orders. Additionally, ETFs come in a wide variety of funds, but savvy investors should evaluate whether these stated benefits, like diversification, truly exist and to what extent. For this analysis, we will examine the IHF ETF and compare it to its top 10 holdings to see if owning a single ETF offers benefits close to those of a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and whether there are better configurations of these stocks that could yield a higher Sharpe ratio or return.

To keep the analysis manageable, we've decided to include only the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of all assets in the ETF. Below is a list of these top 10 holdings and their respective percentage of total assets.

To assess how well these ten stocks represent the IHF ETF as a whole, we'll calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and return, using the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%. The calculations for Beta and return are included in the chart below.

The chart reveals that a portfolio made up of the top 10 holdings would generate a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase. It also shows that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than that of the ETF as a whole. These results suggest that a portfolio of the top ten holdings could provide a higher return with a lower Beta. However, it's important to note that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To determine if the portfolios are statistically different, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

"Dream-Land," one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed finer poems, employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56. Mabbott traces this reference to Virgil, who used it to describe an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world by the Greeks. While Virgil's usage is undeniable, there's a more contemporary connection to consider. Poe was fascinated by German literature, particularly the works of Goethe.

This reference is crucial as it highlights Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt notes the similarity between Poe's "Dream-Land" and Goethe's "Mignon," concluding that Poe was likely imitating the latter. "Faust," a celebrated poetic drama by Goethe, was published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second upon his death in 1832. The second part contains a short poem titled "The King of Thulé," which tells of a king who loses his wife and subsequently his life over his grief and drinking.

Poe incorporates "Thulé" twice in his works. He uses the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but in "Dream-Land," he employs it as a framing device for the entire poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes Thulé as dark, lonely, and haunted by the ghosts of friends, reminiscent of the fate of the King of Thulé in Goethe's poem. The entire poem seems to be a reflection of stepping into Goethe's work.

Goethe, a significant author, would have been known to Poe not only for his respect for Tennyson but also due to the numerous reproductions of his works circulating after his death.

Under California law, could a customer who slipped and fell on an applesauce spill in a grocery store, resulting in injury, be awarded punitive damages if the store manager was informed of the spill twice and failed to clean it up for a half-hour because he was dining? A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages outright. To seek such damages, Palmer must show that the defendant's actions were willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm, as well as that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known the spill's potential harm, considering multiple previous incidents, and that his failure to act was despicable given the ongoing safety issues. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee informed manager Paul Martin about the spill, and he responded he was on dinner break. Another employee notified him at 5:15 pm, to no avail. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell, sustaining a serious back injury. Palmer is suing for damages, and we are considering a motion to dismiss the punitive damage claim. In California, punitive damages can be awarded for a breach not arising from a contract if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud, or malice.” Courts have defined malicious conduct as knowing the probable harm and willfully failing to avoid it. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Almost four years ago, I took a course in Islam at CBC. One of the most contentious topics of discussion in the class was whether or not Islam is a hostile religion. I believe that this question has become even more pertinent today. Looking back on the events since 9/11, I’ve noticed a shift in the mass media’s portrayal of Islam and extremists, ranging from a hostile view to an extreme form of tolerance in America. I don’t think in 2001 we could have imagined a presidential candidate with the name Barack Obama, who has an obvious Muslim background in his family.

The biography of the Prophet is fascinating to me because, according to what I know of the history of Muhammad, it contradicts his personality. From what I’ve learned in the past, I thought Muhammad was a forceful figure who would conquer tribes and force them to convert to Islam. However, the biography portrays him as a martyr who was misunderstood and humbled himself to others, leading people to see the ‘truth’ in his teachings and seek him out.

Moreover, there are uncanny similarities between Jesus’ ministries and the ‘miracles’ attributed to Muhammad. The most notable example is when he multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men. This style of writing makes me believe the authors wanted Muhammad to be perceived as a humble prophet who didn’t need to prove anything, simply living in truth and miracles. This sort of fallacy is particularly concerning because it diminishes the miracle and life of Jesus Christ, as if they are trying to appropriate Jesus’ life and personhood through Muhammad.

Additionally, many stories in the biography seem to serve an agenda of providing proof of ‘witnesses’ or of how people converted to Islam ‘on their own.’ However, many of these stories are third-party accounts, with the author claiming to have heard them from others, who heard from others, and so on. This approach makes the stories seem less reliable and more suspicious.

What bothers me the most about this work is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. However, historical records contradict the idea of Muhammad being a gentle and humble man, and I can’t help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad’s rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus, as they were during his lifetime, were quickly swept aside in the evolution of Christian thought that followed. If we paint a broad picture of this history, we see a trend of Christianity moving steadily away from its roots. Today, we witness an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people persist and may resist new thinking, their influence may not be significant enough to shape the whole. Among Christians, there is a growing historical awareness, a yearning to distinguish the doctrines that were incorporated over time from the original intent of the religion's namesake. This process may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable: a great reversal in the trend of Christian history, a progression back to its original form. A movement will gain momentum, stripping away layers of doctrine one by one, as if the clock is moving backward, until only the essence of what Jesus brought to humanity remains. When this trend reaches the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if living during Jesus' time, the church will remain robust, guiding the way. However, with the theological clock moving backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity in Christendom will reverse into more uniformity of belief and practice. We will see less difference and more similarity among regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind. Throughout history, great reversals have occurred. For instance, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, which later became Christianized. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play out in the Christian religion, undoing history to find the source and reducing diversity in the process. This process will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. Then, what happened since Jesus' lifetime? If we look back far enough in history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation of Christianity. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the notion of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at the core of the religion. However, the Jewish population was not united; they were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

The Jungle exposes the inherent greed and self-centeredness of human nature, demonstrating that people are driven to improve their own lives without considering others, especially those less fortunate. The novel illustrates this through the actions of factory owners and managers, who prioritize their own wealth and success over any cost to workers or the environment. According to Upton Sinclair, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," depicting the immense pollution caused by these factories. The owners show no remorse for the people or animals harmed by this pollution, including the thousands of pens filled with animal waste.

The owners also exploit their employees, forcing them to work grueling hours and providing little compensation. Sinclair writes, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." Workers face layoffs without notice, leaving them without jobs and assistance. The lack of laws or regulations to protect workers allowed managers and owners to operate with impunity, pushing employees to work in horrific conditions. The novel suggests that those who perished in Packingtown were expected to endure the harsh living and working conditions. There were no agencies to aid these workers, and unions often caused more harm than good, lining their own pockets rather than helping the workers. The workers were effectively slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors employ various techniques to evoke specific feelings or attitudes toward crucial subjects. Some of these methods are more successful than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs a multitude of these strategies in his novel The Great Gatsby. Occasionally, he links an adjective with a noun that doesn't typically pair to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. At other times, he imparts meaning to a symbol and then uses it for this purpose. Fitzgerald frequently uses the latter technique with colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald builds up associations for these colors, particularly white/gray and red/pink, which he later employs to remind readers of specific feelings related to important objects.

Fitzgerald imbues white/gray with a sense of uniformity, with white signifying a refined, high-class image and gray representing something older and faded. He introduces this meaning in the beginning of the novel through recurrent use of these colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently “in white” (8), and everyone at Gatsby’s party wears white: Nick in “white flannels” (41), Tom in a “white shirt” (36), and Catherine “powdered milky white” (30). The only time people aren’t in white is when Nick observes Gatsby’s party: “the halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further reinforces these colors by using them to paint common, unimportant subjects: Nick commutes “down the white chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are “gray names” (61) on Nick’s schedule, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses” (28), and he describes ordinary people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19), there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).

Once Fitzgerald has established these meanings, he employs white/gray to convey a sense of unimportance or uniformity around certain subjects, starting with Daisy. After a long period without significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster” (74), making her seem less like a character and more like a uniform addition, something Gatsby desires and yearns for. Fitzgerald continues this technique around Daisy to emphasize her uniformity, such as the “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18) and her appearance in a “white” (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County boasts an agriculturally diverse landscape, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a thriving market for organic, community-supported agriculture food in the region, with numerous local organizations sporting long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching, allowing for educational and financial opportunities. This approach enables landowners to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat and recreational use.

Culture, in essence, is a complex tapestry. It's not merely what it appears to be, but also what it isn't, and what it symbolizes. Culture isn't something uniform or singular, like a specific thing. Generalizations about cultures, such as "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating," are often too broad and simplistic. While acknowledging a culture's general traits is useful, it's more beneficial for a negotiator to grasp the significance of that culture to the situation and how it might influence the negotiation table. When interacting with a foreign culture, one naturally relates it to their own, leading to comparisons. Understanding a foreign culture or mindset can involve exploring its history or recognizing its biases. Instead of judging or altering a culture, one should accept it as it is and operate within its guidelines, especially when negotiating from a weaker position or on foreign turf. Acknowledging traditions and beliefs can help navigate cultural barriers and propel the negotiation forward. Remember, culture isn't confined to national or international borders—most companies within a country develop their own corporate cultures. For instance, some may prioritize long office hours, while others might favor a more relaxed schedule. These nuances can be observed in dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. Even within the same societal culture, there can be vast differences from company to company, or even between regions. Values are particularly crucial to understand, as they provide the underlying reasons for a culture's behaviors. If saving face or communal harmony are valued, a negotiator will avoid publicly shaming their company or superior to succeed. Conversely, if a culture emphasizes a hard-driven bargain, a negotiator won't rush to settle. While these general insights are helpful, it's also wise to learn more about the opponent's personal background to make the negotiation more effective.

The fool, in his hubris, argues that there is no God. St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas, two figures of considerable theological influence, both challenge this notion, each offering their own arguments to prove the existence of the Biblical God. To evaluate their arguments, we must first acknowledge their shared belief in God, as their respective defenses of this concept are the focus of our inquiry. Any deviation from this specific God would render their arguments incomparable. With this in mind, let us explore their arguments. St. Anselm's argument revolves around the notion that God's existence can be understood through faith and introspection. He posits that God is inherently part of our understanding, making the concept of God's nonexistence inconceivable. This idea, while complex and sometimes unclear, suggests that the proof of God lies within our own minds, eliminating the need for external evidence. This is a central tenet of Christian belief, often referred to as faith.

Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, posits that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence alone, without the need for faith. Such an approach would be advantageous for evangelism, as it allows for the recruitment of new converts based on logical persuasion rather than faith alone. Aquinas presents five logical arguments in support of his claim: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument essentially demonstrates the logical necessity for God's existence. If one piece of a puzzle were missing, logical deduction would allow us to understand and prove its existence without physically seeing it.

Sometime around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be known as Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly pursuits and achieved enlightenment, and his teachings eventually gave rise to Buddhism—the most traditional form of which is Theravada Buddhism. This religion, now about twenty-five hundred years old, has evolved significantly since Buddha's time. This change can be observed today, for example, in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated. Both monks and laypeople participate in this event, which, despite Buddha never teaching about it, holds great religious significance. Such differences extend from superficial traditions to the religion's core beliefs. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the perspective of monks and laypeople, has adapted its doctrinal principles over time due to both internal and external influences, ranging from hostile to benign.

Various terms are crucial to this discussion. Internal forces are those originating from within the Buddhist community, regardless of status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces negatively impact the Buddhist community, often stemming from misperceptions of Buddhism, while benign forces, though not necessarily intending to help or harm, may still influence the community. These terms will be frequently used throughout this discussion.

First, we must explore the fundamental tenets of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is composed of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka delves into the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism, such as Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of all things. Recognizing these concepts allows one to break free from Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which ends the trio of attachments: lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules of life, with five precepts for laypeople (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicants) and many more for monks. The most fundamental doctrine is the four noble truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and the path to the end of suffering is the Noble Eightfold Path.

The United States of America and Mexico once shared a long-standing rivalry that spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States emerged victorious and acquired Texas and the American Southwest as new territory. There were numerous other conflicts between the two nations, which finally eased up just before the First World War. Like many other nations, the rivalry between the United States and Mexico began due to clashes over religious, cultural, and traditional differences, as well as competing material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31). This is not uncommon among nations sharing a border, as the proximity often leads to rivalries over shared territory. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that “only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41), as these nations are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, unlike other Latin American nations that have maintained good relations with the U.S. Religious issues created a divide between the two nations, a problem that has plagued many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) states that “if in the twentieth century Americans opposed fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, they opposed Catholicism and monarchy” (p. 86). The rivalry was part ideological struggle and part competition over vital interests, not based on political structure but on religious preferences. This distrust dated back to the animosity between the English and Spanish, making amicable foreign relations difficult. Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during this rivalry period, with most involving territorial issues such as border raids and frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American towns into Mexican territory were a persistent issue until both nations exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97). The rivalry began to ease as Mexico became more dependent on the United States, and it finally ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico in the late 19th century (Schmitt 1974, p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, illness struck suddenly and without warning, leaving me disabled and unprepared. I was a nurse at the time, drawn to the profession due to a deep-seated need for the stability and security it promised. "You'll always find work; people will always get sick," was the refrain I heard as I grew older. So, even though my heart yearned for science or journalism, I chose nursing. Yet, here I was: forty-six, single, penniless, and unable to work. For fifteen years, Social Security Disability has been my lifeline, but it has left me with nothing to call my own. Each day is a battle for security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing is certain anymore, yet one thing is clear: I would not have survived these years without the support of my family and a few steadfast friends.

Life is filled with emergencies, big and small. Some challenges are too great to face alone, no matter how well we prepare. I strongly believe we should stop relying solely on large government systems that are failing. Instead, let's foster a culture of mutual trust and assistance, where we learn to help each other and ask for help when needed.

Conservatives often talk about the rugged individualism that built this country, but it was actually compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources that sustained our forefathers in tough times. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies did not make it alone; they relied on each other.

So, by all means, be prepared. I have emergency supplies, from first-aid kits to canned goods and water purifying tablets. I have flashlights, candles, and matches. If you have the means, consider growing your own food or installing a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you prepare, don't forget to build connections with your neighbors.

Why do organisms adapt and evolve in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that guide the course of evolutionary change? While D’Arcy Thompson asserted in 1917 that "Even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," the same uncertainty persists today. However, recent advancements have applied mathematical modeling to various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis, both in ontogeny and phylogeny. Our research aims to explore how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can reveal the mechanisms behind the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental change. We analyzed X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that form the basis for modeling hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell. We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to understand the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better comprehend macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be visualized as a structure that traverses through 360 degrees of space over time, with each revolution or turn of a coiled shell called a whorl. These whorls move around an imaginary central axis, known as the columella, which runs through the central column of the shell. The enlargement rate of whorls can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, known as a suture. Typically, the largest whorl is the last one, known as the body whorl, and the spire consists of all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the base is the opposite end. The animal exits through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed from various perspectives: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual orientation of a shell is an apertural view, where the aperture faces the viewer and the apex points upward.

To count whorls, first view the shell from the apical side and locate where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are then counted from this line, estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a progression of apertures through both time and space as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be tracked using the coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture, as well as horizontal and vertical radii. This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is established, parameters can be varied and modified to influence the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

In Indonesia, the neonatal and infant mortality rate has barely budged over the past decade, despite the country's progress towards many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets. While strides have been made in child and maternal health, we're still far behind the goal posts for 2015. Let's delve into the reasons why and consider what needs to be beefed up: our health system, perhaps, rather than isolated program interventions.

While we've seen a boost in births attended by skilled healthcare workers, reaching 72%, the picture isn't entirely rosy. Traditional midwives, who can't provide advanced medical care, make up a chunk of this number, contributing to the high maternal mortality rate from conditions like hemorrhage. The uptick in births attended isn't the full story here. We've also seen a dip in the percentage of children under five receiving professional treatment for diarrhea. Postnatal care data is sketchy, but it's clear that it's a concern nationwide, with low rates across the board.

Cesarean-section rates are still subpar at 4%, with a stark urban-rural divide. Urban areas boast a 7% rate, while rural areas lag at 2%. This underscores the inequity in healthcare access, which is heavily skewed towards urban areas. Furthermore, there's a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles, highlighting the struggle for the poor to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

So, as we ponder how to improve neonatal and maternal care, we must ask: should we prioritize developing targeted programs or bolstering the overall health system? Program-specific approaches are tempting. They offer clear, manageable objectives and can yield quicker results. However, they can also lead to funding and resource imbalances, with certain areas, like HIV/AIDS, receiving disproportionate attention. Moreover, running multiple parallel programs can lead to service duplication and an overwhelming amount of paperwork.

Victorian literature often showcases meticulous attention to detail and an emphasis on the upper classes. Two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which diverge from this norm by incorporating elements of mystery and the bizarre, typical of the period. These unusual aspects contribute to the characters' development, offering deeper insights into their motivations and emotions.

“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.”

These novels often use mystery and dreamlike states to convey their themes, with each approach differing. For instance, in Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences reveal his inner turmoil, the things that trouble him, and his understanding of the world around him. When Oliver revisits the shooting in chapter 28, he relives it vividly, as if in a dream, while struggling to find help. This passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the events that unfolded, his dire health situation, and the constant fear and despair that haunt him. The shooting highlights Oliver's helplessness to effect any change, even during life-threatening situations. It suggests that he has little control over his circumstances, reinforced by the sense of defeat and resignation as if old Fagin has broken him.

“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours.”

A couple of years back, I was part of an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged kids. While I could help them with various subjects, my strengths were in English and reading. I was asked to assist a young boy named Adrian, who was struggling with reading. His difficulties were peculiar; he could pronounce certain letters correctly while others were a mystery. He spoke perfect English but was having trouble with the English alphabet. It wasn't until I met his mom that I understood the issue; Adrian could read, but he didn't know the alphabet well. I hope he's improved now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier problem in schools, especially in California. Even a kid who speaks perfect English can struggle with reading. This problem is evident, and solutions aren't straightforward. In Adrian's case, tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations, helped. But for kids who barely speak English, the solution is more complex. There's no single answer. Combining all approaches—dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—is the key to addressing this issue.

Firstly, the dual language system is beneficial. Not just for kids whose first language is Spanish, but for all. Studies show that children in these programs outperform their peers academically. However, fear and misconceptions surround this idea, such as it being a resource drain or unhelpful for the majority. But that's not true. If implemented as the norm, all children would benefit. How do we achieve this? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? Not necessarily. It's more practical to have bilingual aids or tutors to support these programs.

From the moment we are little, many of us are told there's something greater than ourselves, something we can't fully grasp. Some of us attend Sunday school, others visit temples, or delve within ourselves for answers. Many readily embrace the faith passed down by our parents, but some reject it entirely, dismissing the possibility of anything beyond our personal realities. Still, we all journey to define pieces of ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We seek a beacon in the darkness to guide us from the shadows into the light.

"A cardinal," my father replied when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, listening to the rain's relentless drumming on the tin roof above while we smoked. The gutters channeled the rain, drenching the plants along the porch's edge. He stared out into the storm, his eyes half lost in thought, half recalling memories. His once sturdy frame now seemed frail, his clothes loose and shapeless. His hair, thinned, fails to hide the signs of the illness. He gazed out into the rain, avoiding my gaze. I felt alone, afraid, and silenced by my fear of discussing the inevitable. I hugged him, pulled my chair closer, and joined him in watching the falling rain of the June twilight.

My father passed away five days after my twenty-second birthday, in December of that year. The treatments had not lessened his suffering but prolonged it, keeping him alive a few more months than expected. The purpose of his prolonged suffering was unclear to me. The thought of a God who would allow this crossed my mind. I found no solace in prayer that night. If God existed, I believed he had stopped listening long ago.

I declined to witness his passing into another realm. I couldn't bear to watch the life that formed me fade away. I chose to remember him through the life he lived, not how he died. I knew my father better than anyone, better than his own family. I was certain he wouldn't want his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in my bed for three days, awaiting the news, only to find that no one called me.

The classic "Gothic Novel," as Ian Watt puts it, is a paradoxical blend of "old" and "new," both in name and substance, in his book The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both lauded and criticized, praised for its 'terrible sublime' and accused of lacking depth. The original Gothic novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, merged elements of ancient and modern romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole combined old theatrical elements with new naturalistic mimicry in modern novels, labeling it "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). Gothic novels often hark back to medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods, seen as archaic or unsophisticated. The fusion of the more theatrical Gothic and the novel's personal perspective is what has kept the Gothic genre relevant, making it both obsolete and fresh for readers far removed from the original era.

A prominent Gothic theme is the concept of Chivalry. The original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto, retained and transformed the medieval idea of chivalry. Chivalry, representing the ideal knight, was appealing to Gothic writers because of the lack of that ideal in contemporary society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" was idealized and romanticized, hinting at the future evolution of Gothic to Romanticism. Walpole, writing during a politically tumultuous time, may have felt that the supposed morality and inherent goodness of the Gothic era had been lost in modern society. This is evident in his characters, particularly Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits, being described as a brave and courteous knight, even if exaggeratedly so (66).

Supply chain management is the sequence of operations that transforms customer orders into finished products and delivers them. This concept was introduced by Keith Oliver in 1982 and encompasses planning, implementing, and guiding the supply chain to meet customer needs swiftly and efficiently. The six critical components of a supply chain are production, sourcing, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business leaders utilize these elements to deliver superior customer service. Production is the cornerstone of the supply chain, involving the who, what, when, where, and how of making products. Managers must understand market demands to make informed decisions. By examining the market, managers can discern customer preferences and determine which products to produce and in what quantities. After deciding what to produce, managers must choose the optimal production location based on volume, quality, and customer satisfaction. Following this, they focus on scheduling production and maintaining equipment. Production is crucial for the supply chain; each detail must be meticulously planned to avoid future costs in time and money. For instance, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target, where each aspect of the business had a detailed plan, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments. Well-defined processes ensure smooth operations and clear expectations. The second key element in supply chain management is sourcing. This involves strategic decisions about core facility capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. Companies may have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with distinct equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must select the best-fitting division for each product process. Outsourcing can be employed to enhance velocity, which refers to providing quality and flexibility while minimizing costs.

Every day I walk down the streets of Burma, I am greeted by a haunting sign. It reads, "Hitler is alive in Burma," scrawled in black Sharpie on a cardboard held by Ellen Page, the actress from Juno. Burma, or Myanmar as it is officially known, is a country in Southeastern Asia ruled by a stern military junta that seized power in 1962. In 2007, a series of public protests erupted, known as the "Saffron Revolution," led by monks dressed in their saffron robes. The government initially allowed the monks to gather peacefully, but the violence escalated, and the military openly attacked monasteries. Foreign journalists were arrested, and one Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed during a street protest in September of 2007. While the official death toll stands at 13, some suggest the real number could be in the thousands.

This is not an isolated incident. Throughout history, many governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their citizens. Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, while Japanese emperors are considered gods. In our own time, our president, George W. Bush, reportedly holds weekly meetings with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a branch of the Republican Party.

Other notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest authoritarian rule, resulting in a death toll ranging from 200 to 3,000 people. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s saw Hutu militia groups, backed by the government, systematically kill Tutsis and political moderates. And let’s not forget Hitler's "Third Reich," a period of widespread atrocities against Jews and others.

Every time I listen to Duke Ellington’s music, I marvel at his enduring impact on jazz. This longevity is largely due to his mastery of his orchestra, orchestrating complex pieces that highlight each band member’s unique talents. Ellington’s compositions often feature subtle piano interplay, yet he excelled in creating rich, intricate arrangements that allowed soloists to freely improvise while maintaining a cohesive sound.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington’s innovative use of voice as a jazz instrument, as seen in Creole Love Call. This slow, twelve-bar blues piece uses call and response between voice and reeds to add layers of texture and color. The voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound. The muted trumpet and clarinet solos elaborate on the melody, while the full band echoes the first chorus. The climactic chorus features a high-register call and response, backed by syncopated stop time. The final chorus returns to the original structure, with the voice taking on a “growl” technique. A brief tag ends with a vocal run and a dissonant trombone novelty.

This use of voice to enhance tone color is a signature of Ellington’s style. In Hot and Bothered, he combines tight orchestration with tone color, using Bubber Miley’s muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing to create a complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) showcases Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton’s muted trombone in a similar fashion.

She had always felt an insatiable yearning for something, a need that couldn't be satisfied. This longing began when she was 14, entering her teenage years, and it persisted at 17. While she'd defined her desire as someone rather than something, she'd found no interest in boys. Some had tried to woo her, but she remained untouched. She often questioned herself, trying to deduce the cause of her indifference. Years of contemplation offered theories, but no conclusive answers. Therefore, she lived life, always questioning her desires.

A normal day at home was usually peaceful, with parents who rarely argued and a daughter who was both lively and lovable. Today, however, was anything but normal. As she searched for inspiration in her own life, a scream from the kitchen startled her. She rushed in to find her mother on the floor, in obvious pain. "Mom? What happened?" she asked, helping her mother up. "Ow... sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital," her mother gasped.
