With her mother's guidance, she carried her to the car, driven by an urge to help. At the hospital, the scent of disinfectant and fear filled the air, but her mind was focused on her mother. The doctors took her, and she was left to wait in worry.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to reach the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a Mediterranean Diet (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean diet score" (aMed), is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as a lower likelihood of stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet is a version of the Med diet, featuring increased consumption of plant-based foods (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (versus saturated fats), and fish, while lowering intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is allowed.

Previous research has shown an inverse correlation between adherence to the Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular mortality. An intervention trial also found the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in overweight individuals. However, prior studies did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke mortality.

This research followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study—a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six periods from 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed score using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) that assessed nutrient intake over the previous year. More than 95% of nurses continued their participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation checks. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Cases without available records were classified as "probable" and included, representing about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts.

To minimize random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed scores from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from the two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could skew results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to evaluate the association between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combined fatal CHD and strokes) were recorded. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America experienced a severe financial collapse. Unemployment skyrocketed, the housing market plummeted, and many of America’s biggest corporations were left in ruins. This recession continues to this day, raising the question: how did this crisis happen, and how can we prevent it in the future? Simply put, the financial crisis was born from self-centered and naïve political choices that pushed banks and companies into issuing sub-prime loans to an already underprepared and weak financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted, banks found themselves lacking capital reserves and passed this chaos onto the repackaged mortgages and the broader economy.
The roots of this crisis can be traced back to the Clinton administration in 1999. Aiming for a second term, President Clinton sought to boost his popularity by easing lending restrictions, which laid the groundwork for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times warned in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest mortgage underwriter, has faced increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgages for low- and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its profits.” Holmes accurately predicted the consequences, stating, “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, requiring a government rescue like the one for the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As mentioned earlier, and as Holmes foretold, reckless lending would indeed bring about economic disaster.
Many factors combined to send the economy into a tailspin. One key factor was the complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely used leading up to the crisis, further entangling the economy in the housing market. This excessive use of leverage in the housing market made U.S. households and financial markets highly vulnerable to even slight price changes.
The housing bubble inevitably burst, leaving financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities high and dry. The top five U.S. investment banks reported a combined $4.1 trillion of mortgage debt in 2007, an astounding 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the aftermath, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks under stringent regulation. Fannie and Freddie, holding $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That place in your story where you either soar to new heights with your captivating prose or plunge into the depths of your readers' patience. Dr. Merlin has been known to shudder at her keyboard when she finds herself wading through a swamp of unnecessary details, especially when it's not in the thrilling way. Exposition, it seems, is not your friend.

You've surely heard the advice "Show, don't tell," but even Dr. Merlin trips into long stretches of unengaging text. Exposition is that sneaky little voice on your shoulder whispering, "Get the backstory out of the way so you can get to the action (not to be confused with the voice on the other shoulder urging you to reveal every last detail of every character's life)."

Exposition means telling your audience what happened, often in simple, straightforward prose. In a film, it might be when one character shares a history with another like the Ancient Mariner. In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Let's illustrate with an example. Picture a story where you're told that a heroine and her love met at a certain place and time, married in a grand ceremony, and tragically, her husband was murdered in front of her. You wouldn't expect this tale to stretch over two pages, during which both characters only utter a few lines. You'd expect the author to delve into the husband's character, revealing his deep love for his wife through his speech and actions. Similarly, you'd expect the heroine to demonstrate her attachment to him in subtle and significant ways, showing how his presence enriched her life. This character development would allow you to mourn his death with her and, in turn, connect more deeply with the heroine.

In essence, you'd expect more than just the bare bones: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to offer that substance. (*takes a deep breath*) Sometimes it's tempting to skim over certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character who, you know, used to be in the Air Force, is now the night manager of a gas station, has been married twice, has no children, enjoys fishing on weekends, and secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday while indulging in a hearty breakfast of Eggs Benedict.

Pay attention to the meat, not just the bone.

I tuned into two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first, a live NBC 4 report on August 13, 2011, featured a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio who had allegedly stabbed his wife, though her name was not mentioned. His mug shot was shown, and he appeared menacing. The story was given two minutes, which I thought was reasonable given that it was still developing. The second story was about an 18-year-old man named Travis Buyers who was critically injured in a shooting in Sharon Woods. There were no arrests or suspects yet, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed brief, and I suspect this was due to the victim being a minority. I've noticed that media coverage often glosses over stories involving minority victims. Conversely, if a "white" child or adult is involved, it's a different story. The following report was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, likely caused by a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers are offering a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest. The weather report predicted rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures expected to remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. This story was a teaser to keep viewers watching. A robbery at a Clime Road UDF was also reported, with the suspect described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie. I found it unusual that such emphasis was placed on his race. Another story detailed the conviction of Rene Rodriguez, a Texas drug kingpin sentenced to 300 months in prison for conspiring to distribute marijuana. It was unclear why the sentence was stated in months rather than years, and his Hispanic background seemed irrelevant to the story.

There's a unique bond between brothers; it's an unshakable, unchangeable connection. Within this bond, a swirl of emotions exist: love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty, among others. Brothers understand each other deeply, seeing themselves reflected in one another's eyes. This bond is most evident in dire situations, where the raw emotions shine through, whether they're positive or negative. These emotions come at a price, and understanding them means dealing with their consequences. When a brother looks into another's eyes, they see not just another person but their own true self. The actions and consequences of those actions reveal their true character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers delve into this theme and the emotions it sparks. Through a richly described landscape, these boys embark on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment and intense pride collide in the story's climax, and only one brother survives the encounter. The theme is explored through the protagonist, Doodle, and his interactions with others, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which shares the complex feelings of the protagonist and his views of the world, both of which heavily influence his actions.

The protagonist's actions are primarily driven by one key emotion: pride. From their first outing together to their final, tragic adventure, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He had envisioned a brother who would be his pupil, learning all his worldly skills like "…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…". He dreamed of a brother who would race to Horsehead Landing and perch with him in the great pine tree. These dreams were dashed when he realized that Doodle's weak heart made him unlikely to survive, let alone participate in vigorous activities. The protagonist even considered suffocating Doodle with a pillow, a chilling thought for a child his age, but his heart softened when Doodle smiled at him. This simple smile gave him hope, suggesting that his initial conviction was not strong. Deep down, he loved his brother.

The brain, a sophisticated and imaginative information processor, has seen its metaphors evolve from ancient to contemporary. Initially likened to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, a book, and finally, a computer, these metaphors have their limitations and can lead to inaccurate conclusions. As you delve into the brain's workings, remember that each metaphor has a shelf life beyond which it may lose its usefulness.

Information processing begins with your senses, converting physical stimuli like tactile, thermal, auditory, or visual signals into electrochemical messages. These signals are continually transformed by the brain's algorithms, using both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when viewing an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines simple data like color, orientation, and edge location to recognize the box. Top-down processing employs earlier decisions to expedite the identification process, such as distinguishing a black box from a hole.

Attention filters, crucial for information processing, decide the signal's importance and which cognitive processes should engage with it. For instance, while your brain processes every blade of grass when looking at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from individually noticing them. Conversely, your name can be picked out even in a noisy environment. Various processing stages, each repeatedly influenced by attention, shape the final output.

Information must be stored for the brain to process it effectively. Different types of memory exist: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is initially encoded, with unique encoding methods for different stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally (how the word looks), phonemically (how it sounds), or semantically (what it means). Maintaining stored information involves various mechanisms, with working memory, which holds data for around 20 seconds, being sustained by electrical signals looping through specific neurons. Long-term memory is thought to be maintained by the structure of certain proteins.

Many theories describe how knowledge is organized in the brain, drawing from human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that concepts are represented as nodes, interconnected based on their relatedness. For example, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can further connect to “wooden,” illustrating the complex web of associations.

Aldous Huxley's "Brave New World" serves as a cautionary tale about the looming threats of technology and capitalism, illustrating a dystopian society where the individual is overshadowed by the collective. From birth, citizens are conditioned to prioritize immediate happiness over all else, with the World Controller dictating their lives. This can be analyzed through a Marxist lens, highlighting the author's concerns about the developments of such systems. Key terms like homogeny and reification emphasize the commentaries on the flaws of the capitalist economy from Huxley's time.

Capitalism is mocked through the concept of false consciousness, where the general populace remains unaware of their true economic relations. The workers, or "proletariat," are manipulated into consuming and indulging, driven by hypnopædia, thus reinforcing the capitalist structure. The lower classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, are completely unaware of their manipulation, while the upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, may be aware but remain complacent. Hegemony, the idea that one class dominates another, is evident here, with the lower classes buying into the ideology of capitalism and consumerism. The lack of meaningful relationships and the superficial nature of interactions – with comments focusing on physical appearance – further highlight the societal impact of capitalism. Man's free will is suppressed, and emotions are kept in check, illustrating how capitalism can oppress individuals and control their actions.

I've been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Navigating the sprawling campus can be a challenge, especially for freshmen like me who were placed in East Halls dorms, which are far from the center. Walking to classes in places like the Willard building can take up to 25 minutes on a bad weather day. Not long ago, these East Halls were isolated by vast, empty fields, but now they're surrounded by new sports facilities, buildings, and apartments, making it even harder to get around. The solution? Cycling. But it's not just about having a bike; the campus needs to be designed for cyclists too.

Recently, I spoke to a friend who returned to cycling after a hiatus. He said, "Bikes are great. It's the best way to get around, and it's good for you too." Cycling is incredibly efficient - a bowl of oatmeal and a bit of exercise can take you far. I, too, live off campus, and the smartest decision I made this year was buying a bike. Instead of walking to Thomas building, which would take 25 minutes, I can now get there in just 5 minutes by bike. However, Pollock Road, the straightest path to Thomas, isn't always pleasant to cycle on. While walking has its merits, I'm too busy to walk. Without a bike, walking would be my only option, adding an extra 30-40 minutes to my daily commute. Over the course of a week, that's over two and a half hours. Add that to the time spent walking to other classes and appointments, and it's more time than I can spare.
